  "estimatedMinutes": 40,
  "concept": "This unit introduces the second workhorse verb of French — avoir (\"to have\") — and uses it to talk about age and family.\n\nLearn avoir now, right after être:\n  j'ai (I have), tu as (you have), il/elle a (he/she has),\n  nous avons (we have), vous avez (you have), ils/elles ont (they have).\n\nThe single most important thing in this unit: French states age with avoir, not with être. You literally say \"I HAVE thirteen years\": j'ai treize ans. Saying \"je suis treize ans\" is a classic beginner mistake — never use être for age. And don't drop the word ans (\"years\"): \"j'ai treize\" is incomplete. To ask, use: tu as quel âge ? (informal) or quel âge avez-vous ? (formal).\n\nFor family, the core words are le père (father), la mère (mother), les parents, le frère (brother), la sœur (sister), and the grandparents le grand-père / la grand-mère. To say a family relationship you again use avoir: j'ai un frère et une sœur.\n\nA quick note on \"my\": French changes the word for \"my\" to match the noun — mon père (masculine), ma mère (feminine), mes parents (plural). You'll meet this fully later; for now just copy the patterns in the examples.\n\nPut it together: \"Je m'appelle… j'ai [number] ans. J'ai [number] frère(s) et [number] sœur(s).\" Try saying three true sentences about your own family out loud.",
